  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, USA)\n- First international efforts to establish anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks\n- Limited scope and enforcement\n\n2. Key Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Increased international cooperation\n- Development of comprehensive global AML standards\n- Expanded reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n3. Major Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Expanded definition of money laundering\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Beneficial ownership transparency requirements\n\n5. Global Regulatory Approach\n- More comprehensive risk-based frameworks\n- Increased cross-border information sharing\n- Technology-driven surveillance methods\n- Stronger penalties for financial institutions\n\n6. Emerging Focus Areas\n- Cybercrime prevention\n- Terrorist financing\n- Complex financial instrument regulation\n- Blockchain and digital asset tracking\n\nThe legislation continues to adapt to technological and financial innovations.",
